 worth well over my asking price, but a fool like me will sell it for this cheep. A man has to make money to feed his family though. What do you say sir?” The Drul sat back and smiled lazily as Ryvian fished around in his money pouch for the right coins. As Ryvian handed the money to the Drul he heard in the distance a bell marking the middle of the day. Ryvian quickly gestured a salute and, with ring in hands, ran off toward his inn<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Looking into the mirror, combing her hair Lily smiled at herself. She was so exited about her meeting with Ryvian. It had been so long and she hadn’t received any mail from him though she sent letters everyday. Lily had sensed him with her when she needed him. After Ryvian left she was more or less shocked with the events and felt abandoned, but ever time this came over her, she felt a surge of pride and the feeling she got when she was around Ryvian, held close and protected. She had her family there as well to back her when she felt as if she couldn’t make it. <br>
<br>
Her family was just like the rest of the Avi, cleric pairs, one son, one daughter, both born with the gift that in the war of Light was given to them. Valin had fought the Darklings in the passes that blocked off their peninsula from the mainland of Nevil. When he had witnessed so many of his countrymen die he prayed to the gods to give him the power to save his people. The god of life and the goddess of death both agreed that they would help him. They gave Valin the ability to spare the souls of those he killed the journey through the Dark Forest by harvesting their souls in his own, allowing them a small area to dwell in. He learned that after death every creature would become benevolent and be at peace with their passing. The souls and spirits of the deceased would then be given the power over the body of its host. Valin would hand over the power of control to one of his souls in the libraries of them so that he could fight for longer periods of time. His wife also asked for help, the power to heal her husband came from the power and glory of the moon. When the moon reached the full glory of it’s height in the night sky the power of the cleric would be strongest, although always there. A room filled in their heads with the power of the stars and moon. The light in the room would be used and then eventually refilled again as the moon rose and fell. The power was passed onto five Gerial generals that became the warlords of the five powerful cities of the Gerial lands. The power was then passed on from father to son, as was the power of the cleric. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
It was shortly after her leaving though, for her academy, that her mother died of in an accidental fire that had taken her house at the night. Her brother had been home for a visit and was killed trying to save his mother from the burning house. Lily was torn inside and was hoping that Ryvian would be there to hold her and keep her safe, but he didn’t show up. She sunk even lower, but she felt his will pushing her on with life and she went back to school to finish up after the funeral. Her brother had been sent off to the mountain by the Avi class, so she could not attend his funeral, but her mother, they sent to sea on a raft. She had graduated as planned and was ready to see Ryvian there, but again he didn’t show up. She could sense he was near though and wondered if he was avoiding her for some reason. By then she had come to trust in his love and assurance, and in this she felt his love come through. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Shaken from her thoughts by the midday bells, Lily quickly braided her long red hair and smoothed her purple silken dress. She was hoping not to disappoint him and hoped that he would recognize her still after these long years. The Gerial birth rite of longevity was at times tiring, but she felt it gave her just enough time to fully enjoy life and its wonders.<br>
