<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Rylena rose from the cot that she had slept in. She looked out the door to see Ryvian starting up the Galton for the day’s work. He turned to her, but instead of turning away this time Rylena smiled back at him. He looked tired and distanced from the activity that was going on around him; he did what was needed but nothing more nothing of his usual splendid morning canter. She noted to herself that Ryvian seemed different when Lily moved out of her tent, but still kissed her on the top of her head as he held her close to him whispering something into her ear. Rylena couldn’t hear what was said but saw Lily relax and return the kiss. This was becoming a strange morning, she thought. She quickly dressed herself and ran out to get whatever food was being cooked for the morning meal. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp With Ryvian’s accepting her lineage, Lily was more than happy, she was wonderfully lightheaded as the Galton ate their morning meal. The group was getting to know each other better and the grumbling of the few that Alec had rousted were growing less frequent. The time seemed to pass as they mounted their horses and started to move towards the pass. The Galton should reach the pass by midday, and Ryvian would have time to start to learn his special gift, less he destroy his mind with the pressure. Lily would see personally to his training. At this thought a smile came across her face and she looked at Ryvian while he rode just ahead of her talking with Talidon. He was listening like a puppy with eager anticipation for the next lesson. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Ryvian, when you release a soul from your mind does it hurt?” Talidon asked looking at the clouds letting his horse follow Ryvian’s. “Yes and no. When you let one part your mind feels the loss and pain of it comes to you, but the pain as a pain from a cut or a gash is different. It feels more like you’ve lost something that you know you can never replace.” Ryvian said gazing into the mountains. He knew all to well the feeling of loss and regret from his childhood days. The day was already reaching the middle as the Galton rode up to the sheer wall of the mountains. The rock seemed to stretch all the way to the heavens. In the rock face was a door carved during the days of the wars of light. Ryvian had seen these doors before but never what lie on the other side. He knew of the famous keep on the end of the valley that waits behind these doors. Ryvian felt the hair on the back of his neck start to rise when the knowledge of the evils that waited in the valley flooded his mind. He lifted his swords in the scabbards to make sure they were clear. “Lets ride.” He shouted back to the Galton when the doors opened to the trotting horses. Valin had sealed these doors many years after the war to keep out all of the evil that wait in the valley and only an Avi had the special powers to open these doors. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The day was growing humid as the sun beat down on the moving Galton without mercy. Ryvian had made sure that there was enough water to sustain the horses and the others. With many breaks to drink and rest Ryvian was feeling quite sure that they had made it clear any dangers that would harm them when he heard the roar of the Bellitors and the Griffons as the crazed beasts plummeted down on them. The Galton formed the circle with spears loosed and lifted to protect Lily and Rylena as the Gerials surrounded them. Ryvian looked to Talidon and was surprised to see such control of emotions. Smiling he pulled the lance loose from the ring in the stirrup and looked to the sky. He had fought with a griffon once but never with bellitors. The creatures were fierce looking with long wings of golden feathers and a wickedly curved beak. Talidon’s cleric was franticly running around trying to find a safe place to hide as Ryvian studied the moves of the wings and the force of the flight through the air. Ryvian loosed his lance up towards the sky and watched the reactions of the bellitors. He had read once about how the creatures had powerful arms and could catch the spears and lances thrown at them. Almost believing they would catch his lance Ryvian was looking for his extra short sword. The lance flew and caught the first bellitor in the chest knocking him clear from the sky. Riding to the place it fell Ryvian jumped from his horse and landed on the beast pulling his lance from the dead body. He watched the sky as one ward tested his throwing arm and lose his spear to one of the flying creatures. Quickly Ryvian jumped on top of his horse and rode hard back to the circle. Lily had taken Rylena aside and was showing her the way of healing a Galton without bonding accidentally to one of them while the Gerials were standing with the horses in front of them as shields. Ryvian was just reaching Talidon before he threw his spear. “STOP! Don’t throw your spears yet!” he shouted as he saw the heads turn. Talidon’s tail was waving around with energy as the adrenaline ran through his veins. “Use the topes from your tents to tie on to the end of your spears so that if they catch them you can drag them to the ground!” Ryvian shouted to the Galton. Quickly the Gerials rushed to the saddles and tied off the ends of the spears. The griffons were flying in but they tended to land so they could fight with their claws and beaks in close combat. Talidon had stuck his spear in the ground and pulled his sword turning back to look at Ryvian do the same. The two would have to take out the griffons while the Galton would take care of the bellitors. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Talidon had never been in a battle before, not even in a fight that ended in blood of any sort. He was almost overwhelmed with the idea of killing something, but the thought of protecting his cleric, his Rachel, brought a sense of duty to his mind and made him ready for this. He followed closely behind Ryvian with his sword ready. Ryvian charged right into the large beast griffons and slashed without any mercy and without any time for thought or choice. The mind was made up when the two charged into the fray not in the middle. Both Gerials fought with an efficiency born of the Avi kind; Talidon was nearly giddy and becoming very confident when a three of the large monsters rammed him knocking the blade from his hands. With a shout he pulled his boot knife and tried to defend his throat from the talons of the griffons. He kicked and slashed, but was knocked around like he was a small child instead of an Avi. He threw the knife into one of the griffon’s eyes and kicked, but it was not enough to keep the third from ripping a gash in his middle and tearing at his arms with an effort to reach the neck. He was about to give up and let his mind wander to the other side when he felt a wave of blood rush over him. Thinking it was his Talidon relaxed and waited the dark gates to appear, but instead he saw Ryvian’s face through the red sheen of his vision and a hand reach out to his. Taking it, Talidon stood up as much as he could and looked back to the Galton, the troops had pulled out large shields and had covered the women as the bellitors dropped rocks on the small group. Then with a shout the shields were pulled back and the spears were launched into the fleet of creatures. Many fell to the sharp points, but a few caught the spears and tried to fly off. With a tug from the ward and a quick knot to the saddle horn of the horse the bellitors were pulled to the ground and landed with a sickening crunch as the winds and skull crashed to the rocky bottom of the valley. The flying creatures were making for another pass when lightning from the sun it seemed laced out and cut down many of the bellitors from the sky. Lily stood with her arms spread wide, her light red hair being tossed in the wind with the lightly shaded purple dress she wore tugging at her body.<br>
<br>
 The shields went back up and the remaining creatures flew off towards the crags higher in the valley wall. The griffons quickly took off to follow. Talidon looked and saw many more dead griffons than he could remember killing, he had only taken a few before he was knocked over, Ryvian must have killed the rest he though. Stumbling and leaning heavily on Ryvian’s arm Talidon made it back to the rest and Rachel rushed to his side placing her healing hands to his side and arms. Talidon felt the power surge through him and the wounds close. In the back of his mind he felt the feeling of someone else watching him. Surprised he tried to find where the feeling came from. He searched and cried out to the ones watching him from inside his mind. Then they spoke to him. The words were slow and broken but he could understand them; they told him he had fought well and they were proud to have been taken down by a warrior and not a poacher. Realization came to him when they spoke to him; they were the fallen griffons. He had his first souls; he was finally a true Avi. This was his first day as a proud Gerial and Avi. Smiling to himself he looked over to Ryvian as he held Lily in his arms letting her tend to a gash in his scalp. The attack had come quickly and he hadn’t had time to dawn his helm. The gash was very large and the blood ran down his face. After lily healed him she kissed him and he held her closer. Talidon kissed his own cleric and looked to Rylena, she was looking out into the sky with a look of longing on her young, pretty face. Talidon looked over to the Galton as they slowly went about checking each horse. They still had a long ride to the keep, but now they seemed more on edge and ready for another attack or ambush. Neither came and the day ran out with the Galton just arriving at the keep. They would have warm beds and a safe place to sleep for one more night.  <br>
