The night was a restless one for Rylena as she roamed the Keep. She was enjoying herself as she walked from room to room gazing at the giant paintings that adorned the walls. They were pictures of the Great War of light and of the heroes from the time of war. The keep was being lighted by some sort of light orbs that floated above pillars of granite. As the moon rose to the top of the sky Rylena started to grow even more restless half running through the keep looking for something to calm her spirits. Following the winding hallways and endless rooms she finally came to a place that held the sword of Valin. It was in a case that seemed to float on the air and illuminate from the inside. She was amazed at the beauty of it and stunned to see someone else standing beside it admiring the ancient blade. She was about to introduce herself when she saw him pull a small dagger of glowing red and start to pry open the case. Without thinking she rushed over to him, “Just what do you think you’re doing?” almost right after speaking she regretted it. The Gerial turned to her dagger pointed towards her neck. Rylena saw a long scar that ran down his right eye cutting the handsome face in two. She stared at him and his long gray hair as the blade came closer to her throat. He broke her trance when he spoke in a voice that did not seem to fit his image; it was soft with a kindness to it that made her go weak at the knees. He was handsome and rugged at the same time that gave him a mysterious mist around him. “What are you doing up so late? Aren’t you supposed to be in bed with your Avi little cleric?” Taking the dagger away from her neck he stepped back and look up and down her. Feeling her ears growing red she lowered her head and looked at his feet, “I do not have an Avi, I have yet to meet one that has not been taken already.” The Gerial smiled and reached for her hand. “Well, I am called Dean the Quick by my friends, but you can call me Wade. That would be my given name and the one my family and very old friends call me. And I do not have a cleric, anymore.” He said kissing her hand. Rylena was feeling lightheaded and watched him return the dagger that he had pulled. “I would not have taken the blade, I just wanted to feel the weight in my hands.” Rylena smiled and let him hook her arm and lead them away. The feeling of unrest in her had finally left and she felt at ease. Walking back towards the rooms for the Galton and warriors, Rylena asked Wade what he meant when he said he did not have a cleric anymore. He simply pointed to the scar running along his brow that was previously covered by his wavy hair, and the one across his eye. “She was taken from me a very long time ago.” That was all he would say. <br>
<br>
Reaching her room she smiled at him again and his kissed her hand once more and bowed slightly. “Are you leaving in the morning?” He asked her as he slowly moved closer towards her. “Yes. My Galton is going to the human city of Ibium.” She whispered as she felt her back hit the door. “Sounds dangerous, humans. I have known a few in my day; they are not a very open people nor are they kind.” He whispered in her ear as his hands moved to Rylena’s small waist. She felt his breath on her neck as she closed her eyes. He softly kissed the base of her neck and shoulder. She leaned forward, but he pulled back. “I will see you in the morning. I will be waiting outside your door when the sun shines through the window. I feel it is my duty to protect you and keep you safe from the evils of men.” She nodded her head, feeling dizzy, she let him pull her close to him once again and let out a small moan as he kissed her softly at first, growing more passionately on her lips. She felt like something was being torn away from her when he broke the kiss. She opened her eyes to find that he was gone. Almost sad and giddy at the same time, Rylena rushed into her room for the night.<br>
<br>
“Lord, I understand that our fighters are being drawn up from the far corners of the sealed lands. We will soon have to plan a way to take the wall down.” Voltik said to the handsome man sitting on the chair carved from stone for the Lord of the Darklings. The head nodded and waved a hand for his highest general to enter. Voltik shuddered as the Darkling walked into the room like he owned the world. He was an arrogant warrior and devious General. “Master Mala Havoc, I’d like you to meet Voltik, the General that took Zefi so many years ago.” Nodding and shaking hands the two walked over to a map that was placed on the table in front of the throne. “As you both know, the paladins are making themselves open once more, claiming to have a Magjic that is rightfully king. But they cannot be allowed to give the mass this knowledge. I want you to seek out this Magjic Voltik and kill them. I will not be overrun by my own people!” The deep voice shook with a rage that was clear. The Darkling was always in a shadow and never could anyone get a clear look at him. From the depths of his shadow, a hand rose and pointed to the map. “Mala Havoc, I want you to go to the docks that cover the bay and start to train the army. You are the only one that can teach them the old ways and how to regenerate their lost wings. Go there and as soon as the troops are formed I want you to tear down the wall that has kept us secluded to this swamp for the last ten thousand years!” Mala Havoc moved his fist over his heart and bowed. “Consider it done Lord.” With another wave the two bowed again and turned to go see to their duties. <br>
